# Transforming Code Reviews with AI

## Features

**Automated Reviews**: Continuous reviews of the pull requests including incremental commits. 

**Summarization**: Generates high-level summary and a technical walkthrough of the PR changes.Â 

**Line-by-line review**: Provides line-by-line suggestions committable with one click.

**Codebase verification**:  Verifies the impact on the overall codebase and identifies missing changes.

**Insights into your code**:  Ask any questions on your codebase within the pull request 

**Chat about your code** : Chat with the bot around your code.Â The more you chat, the smarter it gets.

**Issue Validation**:  Validates the PR against the linked issues and identifies other related issuesÂ

pull_request.title: Fix adventure dep in spigot-based server
pull_request.body:
From https://github.com/MrXiaoM/SweetMail/issues/51

As you see, Multiverse-Core can not works with my plugin SweetMail in a spigot-based server called `arclight`, which with no `adventure` defaultly.
My plugin SweetMail will adds the four dependencies below into my plugin classloader:
+ `net.kyori:adventure-api:4.22.0`
+ `net.kyori:adventure-platform-bukkit:4.4.0`
+ `net.kyori:adventure-text-serializer-gson:4.22.0`
+ `net.kyori:adventure-text-minimessage:4.22.0`

Multiverse-Core certainly can't find `net/kyori/adventure/text/serializer/plain/PlainTextComponentSerializer` in this situation because my plugin don't need it.

So we should check that is `PlainTextComponentSerializer` exists too.

**Actionable comments posted: 0**
ð§¹ Nitpick comments (8)
apps/desktop/e2e/tests/audio-files.spec.mts (8)
`32-32`: **Scope text clicks to the listbox to avoid accidental matches.** Unscoped getByText can pick up matching text elsewhere in the UI. Scoping to the listbox improves robustness. Apply this diff: ```diff - await page.getByText(otherFile).click(); + await page.getByRole("listbox").getByText(otherFile).click(); - await page.getByText(currentlySelectedFile).click(); + await page.getByRole("listbox").getByText(currentlySelectedFile).click(); ``` Also applies to: 39-39 --- `65-67`: **Avoid relying on nonstandard ARIA role "paragraph"; assert dialog text via the alertdialog container.** This removes dependence on a custom/less-common role and scopes the assertion to the dialog. Apply this diff: ```diff - await expect(page.getByRole("paragraph")).toContainText( - currentlySelectedFile, - ); + await expect( + page.getByRole("alertdialog", { name: "Delete Audio File" }), + ).toContainText(currentlySelectedFile); ``` --- `60-61`: **Assert the popover is closed before invoking the destructive action (deletes).** Adding an explicit check that the listbox closed after selecting the current item helps prevent accidental click interception by an open popover. Apply this diff: ```diff - await page.getByRole("listbox").getByText(currentlySelectedFile).click(); + await page.getByRole("listbox").getByText(currentlySelectedFile).click(); + await expect(page.getByRole("listbox")).toHaveCount(0); await page.getByRole("button", { name: "Delete audio file" }).click(); ``` --- `7-7`: **Fix test name grammar.** Minor nit for readability. Apply this diff: ```diff -test("Audio files are is visible", async ({ audioFiles, electronApp }) => { +test("Audio files are visible", async ({ audioFiles, electronApp }) => { ``` --- `10-13`: **Reduce selector brittleness (nth index and absolute path in accessible name).** - nth(1) is fragile if UI order changes; prefer a stable accessible name or data-testid. - Using a full path string as the combobox accessible name can be environment-specific. If feasible, select by a stable label or add a data-testid. If stable test IDs are available, consider: ```ts await page.getByTestId("nav-audio-files").click(); await page.getByTestId("audio-directory-combobox").click(); ``` Otherwise, confirm that the accessible names used here are stable across CI runners. --- `5-6`: **Use a single data source for expected file names across tests.** You're importing expectedAudioFiles and also consuming audioFiles.expectedAudioFiles from the fixture. Keeping only one source reduces drift risk between fixture state and imports. You could derive the two names from the fixture within each test: ```ts // Inside each test: const [otherFile, currentlySelectedFile] = audioFiles.expectedAudioFiles; ``` Then drop the top-level constants and the import if no longer needed. Also applies to: 14-16 --- `48-49`: **Remove stray comment.** Leftover comment appears to be a dead fragment. Apply this diff: ```diff - // await page ``` --- `51-82`: **Optional: Guard against regressions by asserting no runtime errors occur during the delete flow.** Given the original E2E failure stemmed from an AudioFile runtime error, consider capturing page errors/console errors during this test and asserting none were emitted. This will fail fast if the loader misbehaves again. Example (inside the test): ```ts const pageErrors: Error[] = []; const consoleErrors: string[] = []; page.on("pageerror", e => pageErrors.push(e)); page.on("console", msg => { if (msg.type() === "error") consoleErrors.push(msg.text()); }); // ... existing steps ... expect(pageErrors, `page errors: ${pageErrors.map(e => e.message).join("\n")}`).toEqual([]); expect(consoleErrors, `console errors: ${consoleErrors.join("\n")}`).toEqual([]); ```

issue.title: fix: Add DISABLE_HTTPS support for WebSocket URLs in system-config.js
issue.body:
## Fix WebSocket connections when HTTPS is disabled

WebSocket connections were failing when `DISABLE_HTTPS=1` because the URLs were hardcoded to use `wss://`. 

This adds support for the `DISABLE_HTTPS` environment variable so WebSocket URLs use:
- `ws://` when HTTPS is disabled
- `wss://` when HTTPS is enabled

**Changed:** Added inline conditionals to `system-config.js` for protocol selection.

Introduces a revolutionary community-driven insurance system that creates a financial safety net for Justicebit escrow transactions, turning risk into opportunity through collective protection.

- **Proportional Rewards**: Contributors earn from premiums and share in pool growth
- **Risk Mitigation**: Comprehensive protection against fraud and unresolvable disputes

## ð¡ Economic Model
- **2% Premium Rate**: Affordable protection for all escrow sizes

- **Judge Validation**: Leverages existing judicial system for claim validation
- **Self-Sustaining**: Premiums fund both payouts and contributor rewards

- **High-Value Transactions**: Protection for expensive purchases and services
- **Unknown Counterparties**: Added security when dealing with new sellers/buyers
- **Cross-Border Trade**: Extra confidence for international transactions
- **Business Operations**: Insurance for recurring commercial escrows

## â Verification

- Ready for mainnet deployment and community adoption
